What should it do, the ČSSD? The Czech Social Democrats in Prague know neither Voldemort nor the "pastry shop".
The new councillors of the capital from the ranks of the ČSSD will obviously have to overcome certain language barriers in order to be able to understand their old-new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague Council and in the city council at all.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz has "tapped" members of the new Council from the ČSSD a little how they master the notorious slang that has become established in recent years, when today's coalition partners were at the helm in Prague.
The coded vocabulary introduced by Prague's political elite in the bygone era of Mayor Pavel Bém is borrowed from some of the best-known actors, situations and causae.
Surprisingly, it turned out that the new councils are somewhat in the dark about these new terms.
At least that's what they claim.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I don't know."
"I'm more of a newcomer to Prague politics," Lukáš Kaucký, the new councillor for culture, reacted to the test of the "godfather vocabulary".
But councillor Karel Březina - a political veteran - also reacted in a similar way.
For example, the term "golf hole".
"That is the only expression of those you present to me here, which I use from time to time."
"Other than that, I don't think much of slang."
From the vocabulary published by Tageblatt Aktuálně.cz in June before the ODS election congress, the editors picked out six terms, especially those that are notoriously associated with the Prague magistrate.
The Socialists and Democrats should define the terms "Voldemort", "largest Prague golf hole", "go to the pastry shop", "bull's neck", "betrayal of the capital" and "verblechen".
Three Prague councillors agreed to the test, the fourth - Antonín Weinert, the future head of the Prague school system - first promised to take part in the conversation, but then did not even pick up the phone.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, rejected the test from the outset.
"I don't care about these things and I don't judge how the bourgeois democrats talk to each other."
"What is important to me is how we understand each other in the context of our programs," he countered.
As already indicated, Lukáš Kaucký allegedly did not recognize in the above-mentioned headline that the influential entrepreneur and friend of the ex-mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek, was mentioned.
The term "Voldemort" says nothing to Kaucky and the only term he correctly guessed during the test was "the largest Prague golf hole".
"This is the Blanka tunnel," says Kaucký, but added to the safety: "But I know that more from the newspaper."
And jokingly: "I will probably have to take a language course."
The "golf hole" is then correctly deciphered not only by matador Karel Březina, but also by environmental councillor Lukáš Plachý as Tunnel Blanka.
But both Social Democrats also know who the term Voldemort stands for and Lukáš Plachý even suspects where this figure can be found and thus also what it means to "go to the pastry shop".
"I think that means going to some Prague restaurant," Plachý is quite close to the solution to the riddle, knowing that this is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
In agreement with Březina, however, he asserts that he drew this knowledge more from the newspaper than that this vocabulary was peculiar to him.
Judging by the test participants, there does not seem to be any similarly naturalized slang among the Social Democrats.
"I also asked my colleagues, but obviously we really don't have anything like that."
"We call each other by name, sometimes we also use abbreviations or nicknames," says Petr Hulínský, chairman of the Prague ČSSD - casually called "Hulda" by his party colleagues.
"At school I was called Bříza (birch), but I don't know if my colleagues call me that," Karel Březina tells us about his nickname.
The newspaper Deník Aktuálně.cz tried the name and lo and behold - it works.
Councillor Weinert is friendly to the party comrades the "grandpa" or less friendly the "old man", the representative Miroslav Poche, who attracted attention before the elections by machinations in party sponsoring, is called "Igráček" (well-known Czech Lego figure) by some colleagues.
Nicknames are thus the only thing that the Social Democrats allow in intra-party parlance.
Hulínský allegedly does not like being called "Hulda", but Deník Aktuálně.cz registered another nickname of the Prague chairman.
His nickname "Doctor of Rubber Club Rights" allegedly has to do with the fact that Petr Hulínský earned his title Doctor juris at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and published a brochure
Women who are labeled witches in Burkina Faso usually share some common social characteristics.
They tend to belong to the older generation, they cannot find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women "becomes" a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are quite rarely affected by this fate."
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, because they help with the work and give birth to children," says a nun, describing the situation that cares for more than one hundred women who have been outcast by their communities in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government now decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And for this reason, he published a brochure intended to prevent the "witch hunt".
But there's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out the dilemma of written education.
Being accused of witchcraft is also common practice in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men who doused her with kerosene and simply set her on fire.
This incident was also reported by the BBC server.
The perpetrators claimed, however, that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil is inflamed, which is used for ritual anointings.
This was after the group tried to "exorcise an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by the people here regardless of their education.
"Der Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Eaters of human souls are a danger in the past as well as today," he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch-hunt, the Gambian president himself got involved last year.
"President Yahya Jammeh unleashed a monstrous witch hunt after his aunt's death, as they allegedly participated in her deaths and would now try to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To this end, he called on shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguards, forcibly abducted arrested women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the incarcerated people were forced to drink a decoction of plants with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive their stay on the farm.
It was only due to international pressure that the nearly one thousand prisoners were released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the stove - but still pays higher rent
An elderly stocky man is leaving the RPG Byty client centre of the "coal baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm is a folder with three new leases for three apartments: for his own apartments and those of his daughters and his son, who is currently serving a prison sentence.
All three have just had their rent increased as part of the so-called "deregulation".
Instead of 3500 crowns monthly rent, the son is to shell out 4100 crowns next year for a 2-room apartment with kitchen of the second category.
"And there is not even running hot water in the apartment and you have to heat in a simple coal stove," he angrily taps his finger on the new lease of the son, which he has a power of attorney to sign.
"But what - I signed," he explains, half upset and half resigned.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants simply not to sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it plans to publish instructions on how to take action against such contracts.
But the man just waves it off.
"One says this, the other that," he makes a grim face.
The Ostrava region thus becomes a large "deregulation laboratory".
After New Year, this deregulation is imminent for most rental apartments in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not yet paid rent in line with the market.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "laboratory" in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already packed at nine o'clock in the morning this Tuesday.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a calling device.
"Rent 2011" is how a special touch panel lights up on the touch screen.
Briefly tapped and the device spits out a number note.
As soon as we have deciphered the number "157" and it beeps on the large display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later it's your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enters the waiting room to ask for the rent, but the rush in the waiting room apparently does not apply to the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance matters and the like.
From mid-November, the envelopes with the new leases will flutter into the mailboxes of most tenants of the 44,000 apartments in RPG's portfolio in the Ostrava region.
In the letters, RPG Byty proposes a rent increase of about 15 to 38 percent.
The special counter for the new rents in the client centre has been open since 18 November.
"The action runs for a little over a week, which means it's just the beginning," the ladies behind the counter answer after a moment of hesitation when the "client" turns out to be a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former miners' homes are a hot topic.
Before the elections, Lubomír Zaorálek, Vice-President of the ČSSD from Ostrava, had taken up this issue quite loudly, no wonder that today the newspapers are full of it.
"Twenty years I want a new floor from them."
"Not even ne besch. They could change toilet goggles," says the man mentioned at the beginning.
So far, according to the employees, pensioners in particular are queuing up at the counter to see for themselves whether they really receive the promised rent reduction that RPG promises them if they sign the special offer on time.
Other tenants who sign the new lease by 15 December will also benefit from a half-reduced February rent.
So far, however, "deregulation switch" in Havířov is anything but overloaded with demand.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 were here for rent in 2011," estimate the counter clerks.
RPG offers individual rental agreements on its websites as well as blackboards where it seems necessary.
However, if the tenants do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
"This is not meant to be a threat, but is to be understood as information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure," RPG explains on its websites.
"Nobody goes to court here," says one of the employees of RPG Byty, and a man on the street in front of the client center at least partially agrees with her.
"I have 13,000 (crowns) pension, 5,000 of which I have left for food, where should I get the money for a court case," he says.
Then the employee becomes insecure.
"Let's see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and so people are still waiting," she points out.
The regulated rent ends in most of the Czech Republic on New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty, the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing level of rents is not even sufficient for the maintenance of the housing fund," argues Pavel Klimeš, the director of the housing portfolio of RPG Byty and - especially the neglect of the housing fund, criticized by the angry tenants, is the main reason for the rent increase, according to the homeowners.
While RPG was able to invest four billion in the apartments from the rents collected between 2005 and 2010, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is said to be 5.2 billion.
On the large-format LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room of Havířov, a few red glowing information appears again and again.
"The rent increases in 2011 of 15% or less affect 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG's apartments."
"This always means a maximum of CZK 7.50 per square meter per month," reads the LCD monitor.
Only 400 apartments from RPG's portfolio increase rent by 38 percent.
"In these cases, it's about increasing extremely low rents of CZK 19.66 per square meter," RPG argues.
With 2600 apartments, the rent will remain at the same level next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not skyrocket rents, but will happen gradually within four and eight years.
What more - the company imposes another obligation on itself: All income from the rent increase (see diagram) the company wants to put back into the apartments, especially in heat savings - in new windows and in thermal insulation.
But - primarily these should benefit those people who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The Arch.Design design and architectural studio, from whose studios a whole series of renowned Brno buildings originate, counted on the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the first drafts for the new Avriopoint building.
With wise foresight, because most of its 90 employees are of baby boom age and the company wants the designers and architects to return to work as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility of working shorter hours, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding profession and child welfare.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and from the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and qualified personnel and operation have been provided for a period of 2 years.
After exhausting the funds (2 years), the company is Arch.Design obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for another 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of the application.
The children are taken care of all day by qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but several children alternate throughout the day.
The kindergarten operation is flexibly tailored to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is still comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, but they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time, eliminating the stress of late picking up the children from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also developing here.
Arch.Design thus joined the ranks of Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, who are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Check out Gaudi's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local inhabitants nicknamed the house with its organic shapes "bone house".
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection do you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade looks even more three-dimensional, dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and strips.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district, on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the conversion of a house from 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one, but in the end he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper conversion.
However, the Casa Batlló tenement house was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created and the use of mosaics on the façade was also his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also contains other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "bone house" by the local inhabitants because of its organic forms.
Others called it the "yawning house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique for the time, with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination already seems a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all building regulations of the time and was by no means deterred by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified by the result two years later when it was completed that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors were also offended by the fact that the building with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only fifteen days after the neighbourhood's request to do so, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for connecting spaces with each other.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger company could chat comfortably without having to forego a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí's renovation also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Also impressive is Gaudí's play with light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the atriums.
The play of these two colours gives all floors of the house maximum light.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Casa Batlló, which was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is opened to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a fairly lucrative business, the visits were maintained, and they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the monument is not a cardboard handle, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon turrets, you should try to make friends with one of the inhabitants of the house and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed frame? Women have different desires than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and grate make the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, height, state of health and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which the mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Case in point?
In a weekend house that does not heat regularly, latex mattresses are not well suited because they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough venting tubules in the core and lie on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: It is therefore not excluded that mold forms under them.
Of course, what you are used to also plays a role in the choice.
Anyone who has been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will find it difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"I think all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can't sleep properly here anymore."
"For their battered shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of viscous foam (memory foam - a shape memory polymer)."
"Among other things, I recommend these to diabetics who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they can hardly receive the 'information' from the joints and the skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That's why years ago I bought many ice hockey players, but also other customers, these mattresses with viscous foam (memory foam).
"Today, this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others."
And you don't necessarily have to be a famous hockey player to appreciate the benefits of viscous foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it literally nestles against the warm body.
Nowhere does it press, at night you don't roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep much better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against bedsores (gangrene).
When choosing the mattress size, you should still add the length of the soles of the feet to the body size, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman, who are about 180 cm tall, need such a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, i.e. a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, for example singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For the sake of comfort and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for the slightly bent arms," advises Helena Prokopová, the guild master of upholsterers and interior decorators, who has been dedicated to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years and also presents this topic at technical schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own grid and mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the grates at different heights and this is by no means possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with feather skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be on the mold layer and the fine padding.
"You must not feel the feathers with your hand or when sitting down," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a special type of grate.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and pad like grown together Siamese twins have no place in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common practice today.
And since you lose between 0.2 to 0.75 liters of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve).
This is another reason why experts reject advertising slogans that promise mattresses a lifespan of up to 25 years, even a lifetime warranty.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is advisable to use a mattress protector that can be easily peeled off and washed.
Even though today mattress covers are usually made with a wrap-around zipper, so that you get two halves after opening (immensely important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially carried out alone, often seems like the unequal fight between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in bed instead of a grid?
Out with it!
Or at most for a bed for unloved guests and for a single night.
Even so, you should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there are none in it) and mattresses with spring skeleton and 15 cm minimum height with so-called pocket spring core and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a surface.
For non-adjustable slatted frames with 14 to 18 spring strips (slats), latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always pay off gratings with a larger number of slats, ie of 28 or more spring strips, with lumbar support and the possibility to regulate the slatted hardness.
Mattresses with a spring skeleton do not belong on adjustable slat frames, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the spring strips, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special attachment of the spring strips, which makes it possible to press in the spring strips or even to angle them so that they allow the punctual sinking of the sleeper's shoulder.
Especially for men with broad shoulders an important thing.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started to use soft zones for the shoulder area in "men's mattresses".
Also the ladies are thought of - they are granted these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, point-elastic wing spring systems (Lattoflex) or gratings with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion suspension are intended.
The pressure is distributed to several points, which reduces the tension.
But - if you use a bad (too large and full) pillow for the right mattress and right rust, most of the benefits are lost again.
Again, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Therefore, a 50 x 60 cm cushion seems ideal, as the Scandinavians like it, for example.
In the lateral position, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the grate or the soft zone in the mattress) should compensate for the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the former (hay-filled) straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials, or at least their admixtures.
The new magic word for mattresses is also "organic".
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils are increasingly being used for the production of polyurethane foams - for example, castor oil and soybean oil.
Soy is probably used by all known manufacturers.
"Organic in mattresses means that their core consists of materials of purely natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček from the company Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread fresh forest or lavender scent while sleeping.
Here, too, a distinction is made between men and women.
While men use a "cooling" plant extract of birch leaves so that the mattress cover can absorb heat and cool the body, the covers for women have a "warming" effect.
Extracts of red peppers stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets comfortably warm while sleeping.
And today's favorites?
Mattresses made of cold foam (it has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
By combining the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foams and viscous foams, multi-zone mattresses are created that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have to shell out 7000 crowns and more.
However, health mattresses are usually subject to lower VAT because they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to receive this advantage.
As you can see, saving on the mattress and the grate is not so easy.
Every now and then there are special offers from manufacturers and retailers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with quilted viscous foam Memory for CZK 11,990.
The second one is free.
It was the material Tempur that ushered in the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at an almost cosmic pace.
No wonder, as they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads during launches.
Tempur becomes soft in heat, in a cool environment it solidifies again.
Thus, it adapts perfectly to the human body and distributes body pressure in an optimal way.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure burn, but also generally increases sleeping comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are not only used for mattresses, but also for other health products, such as special foot pads, which are intended to provide relief for the legs and vessels.
Local manufacturers use, for example, the foams Eucatherm C, Twinsaver or similar products.
More and more parents want people monitoring devices to keep the kids under control
The fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to search for cars, can locate people just as well, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently with the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette packet but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been terrified by the case of the missing Anička and so they are looking for ways and means to better protect their children.
Even at the price of an invasion of their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases there can be misuse of such devices, for example if you put it in someone's pocket without them knowing about it, but we have not had such a case so far."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things when they don't want to be controlled."
"Initially, the mobile phones aroused great expectations among parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new monitoring devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned abductions, the kidnapper practically always checks whether the child has any electronics with him that could be used to locate him."
"Today it's the mobile phone."
"If such surveillance devices were to be used more widely, they would seek them out as well, as their sale would certainly be accompanied by massive advertising."
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, she acknowledges that similar devices can be helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Roberta Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both cars and people, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
"The device can be adjusted so that it reports the respective position at certain intervals."
"Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last position of the person concerned is available."
"With more expensive devices, even an inclinometer is integrated, which means that if you fall down and remain motionless, the device immediately sends a warning stating the position," claims Mr. Čech.
In his opinion, similar services could also be performed by intelligent mobile phones with navigation, you only need to install special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are either matchbox-sized devices that resemble trailers or smaller cell phones.
There is always the danger of losing them.
According to Mr. Pilin of Macro Weil, devices that look like normal digital watches are currently being tested.
"This has the advantage that the possible attacker does not have to recognize at all that it is a monitoring or locating device.
"Or he only notices it after a certain time, which gives the police a head start," he adds.
No matter in which direction the development goes - towards wristbands or pendants, the same technology is always used as for vehicle tracking.
In other words, the combination of the location function using the GPS system (just like the navigation system in the car) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position.
The army has so many fuses that you could wrap the whole of the Czech Republic But they only last two years.
The Czech army has bought 445 kilometers of fuses, with explosives to be detonated.
The year before, the Ministry of Defense had already delivered 224 kilometers of fuses to the army camps.
It is reassuring to know that the armed forces have provided for 225 years.
The problem is only the durability of the fuses - two, but no more than four years.
The army bought the fuses from the joint-stock company STV Group, a. s. for a paltry 40 million crowns.
In its justification for purchasing this enormous amount of fuse, the General Staff MF DNES replied that the soldiers would consume about 60 kilometers of fuses annually.
According to the research of army pyrotechnicians, whom MF DNES approached, this statement shows that the entire army would have to undergo extremely intensive pyrotechnic training every year - from all generals and officers of the army command, to the secretaries and cleaning ladies.
Defense Minister Alexandr Vondra and Army General Vlastimil Picek not exempt.
This is the only way to justify the considerable annual consumption of sixty kilometres of fuses.
By the way, this length corresponds to 25,000 detonations.
But even so, these army stocks would last for more than ten years.
If, however, the old rule of experts still applies that two meters of fuse are sufficient for the training of every new professional soldier, then the army has created a reassuring supply for the already mentioned 225 years through these new purchases - also from the point of view of the increased demand of the pioneer and special units.
Soldiers of the Rapid Deployment Brigade recently complained to Defense Minister Vondra that they had almost no cartridges for small arms, so that shooting exercises are severely limited due to the lack of resources.
Not to mention the lack of underpants.
"I also can't think of why they buy so many fuses from us."
But that's ultimately their decision, they'll know what they need them for."
"For us, the army is a good customer, which we as a dealer would like to accommodate as much as possible," says Jan Děcký, Sales Manager of STV Group.
Jan Pejšek, the spokesman for the Ministry of Defence, justifies the purchase of hundreds of kilometres of fuses by saying that the army had stocked up on this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký from STV Group only speaks of a four-year service life of fuses and police and army pyrotechnicians only two years.
"With perfect storage, the four years mentioned are probably also possible," admits one of them, who wants to remain anonymous so as not to be accused of criticizing the army as a soldier.
At the end of its useful life, all ammunition must be thoroughly tested to ensure that it is still reliable and does not endanger the lives of the soldiers.
However, these tests are not free, but cost more money.
Another argument of the Ministry of Defense is the volume discount for the 445 kilometers of fuse.
"They cost us sixty percent less than last year's delivery of 244 kilometers," spokesman Pejšek tells us the position of the buyers of the Ministry of Defense.
Just for comparison: The annual consumption of fuses by police pyrotechnicians who liquidate ammunition from the Second World War or the Soviet fraternal army has barely exceeded 1,500 meters for several years.
And the police only ever order such quantities of this ammunition as they can consume before the end of their useful life.
Already because of the safety of the pyrotechnicians, in addition, one keeps open the possibility of flexible purchases of more modern and thus also reliable fuses.
The Ministry of Defense already has huge problems in liquidating tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the two hundred thousand Czechoslovak People's Army was preparing for its campaign to the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians mentioned by MF DNES, in a few years the Czech armed forces will face the same problem in the liquidation of hundreds of kilometers of old fuses that they have bought so "cheaply" today.
To this day, the contacts I have gained thanks to the competition come in handy.
The winning placement in the "Small Business of the Year" competition helped Lukáš Pytloun sell the franchise of his hotel.
The winner of last year's Small Business of the Year competition was Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
The story of his success seems like a film scenario.
Lukáš Pytloun liked to travel.
It was only abroad that he realized that Liberec lacked good accommodation at reasonable prices.
From the savings from his holiday work abroad and with the help of a bank loan, he bought a dilapidated house with five apartments.
Considering that he was a sixth-semester university student at the time, this was certainly a courageous undertaking.
"The price-quality ratio at the time annoyed me and so I tried to do something about it," says Lukáš Pytloun.
He rented the first reconstructed apartment to foreign workers.
He immediately reinvested all his profits in the house, which he then gradually converted into a guesthouse with 54 beds.
Since then, in just seven years of entrepreneurial activity, he has managed to open four guesthouses, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of over 300 beds of all accommodation categories in Liberec.
Until recently, the most comfortable of them was the four-star hotel "Pytloun Design Hotel".
This year, another first-class hotel was added.
"We have just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov u Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other interested parties in the franchise of the Pytloun hotels have already registered," says the number one entrepreneur from last year.
"A large part of this license sale for operating hotels was the victory in the "Entrepreneur of the Year" competition," adds Mr. Pytloun appreciatively.
The victory has brought him greater notoriety, even popularity, in Liberec and the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, often they even congratulated me afterwards and I have to say that felt really good," he recalls.
I really recommend everyone who wants to create something to participate in this competition.
You don't have to win right away, every visibility is good.
He says that to this day he benefits from contacts and acquaintances that otherwise would not have happened at all.
"I still have regular business relationships with some of the people I met thanks to the competition."
In his opinion, the fame associated with success is also reflected a little on each of his employees.
And there he has about seventy.
"I notice greater loyalty and pride in them that they are part of something that is universally recognized."
I really don't see this as just a personal success, no, it's the result of the good work of all of us."
"My name has just come to the fore," says Lukáš Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successors a quieter year than we had in Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the consequences of the crisis.
Thanks to his determination, Farmet has the worst behind him.
Karel Žďárský, the owner of Farmet, received the award for first place in last year's Vodafone Company of the Year competition.
At that time, the jury praised the efforts with which he turned the small tool shop in Česká Skalice into a company that generates hundreds of millions in sales.
"I can say that this recognition has encouraged not only myself, but also all my employees and strengthened our self-confidence in the fight against the competition," says last year's winner.
At the beginning of Farmet's history was the effort to do something useful.
And when the state offered his father Karel Žďárský a small workshop for lease as compensation for the property confiscated by the communists, he did not hesitate for long, abandoned his career in the company where he had been employed until then and founded his own company for the production of plastic tubs with a few of his father's comrades.
A short time later, they began to focus on vegetable oil presses.
Within 18 years, they have become the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
But it was only through its success in the aforementioned competition and its medialization that it also entered the consciousness of the non-specialist public.
"Not only did our customers become much more aware of the Farmet brand, but our foreign partners also began to attach greater importance to being able to work with a company that had achieved the greatest possible success in their country," says Karel Žďárský.
For Farmet, however, the past year was not only marked by victory euphoria.
The appraisal was based on the company's economic results in 2008 and part of it in 2009.
And 2009 was the most difficult year for the sale of toolmaking products.
The crisis, which at that time shook not so much the citizens but mainly the companies, just reached its peak - many companies were forced to stop their investment projects and limit the purchase of new equipment and technologies.
"Of course, we couldn't escape this situation either."
"Sales fell by 40 percent, we had to cut production and even resort to layoffs," explains Karel Žďárský.
A viable company sometimes has to take such unpopular measures.
However, it was possible to get the situation under control and keep the company in the black, even if with lower profits than before the crisis.
There was one thing the company was unwilling to compromise on – investment in research and development.
"With the grant, we built a research and training center, we encouraged our presentation at international fairs and won top prizes at domestic exhibitions," says Žďárský.
Everything shows that we have overcome the crisis.
Sales are growing again and with them the number of new employees.
"I wish the new winner a lot of joy in winning - but in a calmer atmosphere," says Karel Žďárský.
An opinion poll that does away with nonsensical regulations
The opinion poll on the "absurdity of the year" is part of the business competition for the fourth time.
Some nonsensical regulations have already been eliminated.
The dubious winner of the next year of the opinion poll "Absurdity of the Year" was the obligation to create documents on authorities that are available online.
This is how more than a third of not quite four thousand voting entrepreneurs decided.
For example, the social security administration demanded a paper extract from the commercial register, even if the civil servant could have retrieved it with two mouse clicks.
Thanks to the opinion poll, this is now changing.
"In the future, the Czech Social Security Administration will no longer require extracts from the Commercial Register when carrying out inspections of social security payers," said Jana Buraňová, spokeswoman for ČSSZ.
The purpose of the opinion poll "Absurdity of the Year" is to take a close look at all the regulations and orders that entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic have to comply with and to repeal the nonsensical ones.
This year, for the fourth time, this is part of an entrepreneur competition organized by the Czech. Wirtschaftszeitung (HN) and is enjoying growing popularity among the public.
If last year about three thousand people took part in the vote, this year there were already four thousand.
No wonder, because there are still a lot of legal obligations that serve solely to hinder the company's activities.
"As far as the number of income tax forms is concerned, for example, we occupy a leading position in the world," notes Karel Havlíček from the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Traders of the Czech Republic.
Simplifying business activity has been the proclaimed goal of all governments in recent years.
Compared to the world, however, the situation in the Czech Republic has hardly improved.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranks 74th in terms of business conditions, eight places lower than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was announced for the first time in the year and takes place every year according to the same scenario.
Anyone can report administrative and bureaucratic nonsense from April until the editorial deadline of the competition at the end of September.
The web address www.firmaroku.cz is used for registration. The organizer of the competition then selects seven candidates for the "Antipreis" and lets the public vote www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz via the Internet on the websites.
The absurdity that gets the most votes wins.
More than a hundred, more precisely 105 senseless regulations and orders have already been registered for this year's opinion poll.
The tips come not only from entrepreneurs, but also from professional associations and journalists.
Among the nominated "finalists" of the competition are, for example, provisions that maintenance vehicles for motorways and expressways have to pay tolls or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two toilets must prepare every two years.
The list of this year's "seven" is published on the pages of the competition.
The announcement of the competition at the beginning of November on Prague's Wenceslas Square is part of a happening in which personalities from political and public life regularly participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, Director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Tradesmen of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Czech Republic, were present at the highlight of the competition.
"Where the state throws sticks between the legs of entrepreneurs, there can be no real economic recovery, so my goal is to repeal at least thirty paragraphs every year, which today still make it unnecessarily difficult for entrepreneurs to do business," said Martin Kocourek, Minister of Industry and Trade.
The efforts to get rid of nonsensical arrangements are having an effect.
In 2007, people were most disturbed by the obligation imposed on entrepreneurs to notify the trade office at the place of their permanent establishment three days in advance of their intention to go to an exhibition or funfair with an exhibition stand.
This obligation was abolished by an amendment to the Trade Act.
The obligation, which received the second largest number of votes in 2007 - the obligation to report to the employment office business trips of employees of up to 30 days - was abolished by the law on the so-called "Green Card".
And - all good things come in threes:
To the absurdity of 2009, the regulation was chosen, which required physiotherapists to have a mirror, a refrigerator and two bathroom scales in the consulting room.
This regulation was somewhat mitigated by the Ministry of Health this year - the refrigerator requirement was eliminated.
A new category recognizes socially responsible companies
Evaluation criteria are humanitarian, environmental, educational or sports projects
A novelty in this year's fifth year of the competition of the business newspaper (HN) is the category "Responsible Company of the Year 2010".
The basic idea of this competition is to promote reasonable and fair ventures.
"We want to support companies that are aware of the impact of their business activities on the environment and support socially responsible initiatives," says Patrik Bartholdy, regional manager of the mobile phone company Vodafon, which is the announcer and guarantor of this competition, as well as the "Rebel of the Year" competition.
For this year's first year of this special subcategory of the main competition Vodafon Company of the Year, companies registered for which success is not the only long-term goal.
The story of each of them is extremely inspirational and would provide enough material for an independent article.
Although they are diametrically opposed in the subject matter of their activity, their efforts still have a common denominator - support and consideration.
For example, this is about handicapped people, personal problems or the health of one's own employees.
Among the fourteen finalists from all over the Czech Republic was the Prague-based software company Et Netera, which promotes the emergence of non-formal sports teams among its employees, who then participate in numerous tournaments in various sports.
Another example of a responsible company from the Pardubice region is the company Isolit-Bravo, which has been the main sponsor of an endowment fund for handicapped children for seventeen years.
A paper mill from Poděbrady also takes exemplary care of its disabled employees, who make up 70 percent of its workforce, for which it was awarded the title "Responsible Company of the Central Bohemian Region"; in the Vodafone Company of the Year competition, it took third place within this region.
In the Olomouc region, the winner was the accounting firm MiRyz Soft, which, among other things, introduced a fluid working time reduced to an average of 35 hours per week without a proportionate reduction in wages.
At the award ceremony, the jury also acknowledged the fact that the company mainly buys from Czech manufacturers, supports citizens' initiatives in its surroundings and works according to environmentally friendly principles.
"We strive to recycle as much as possible in order to minimize the impact of our business activities and administration on the environment," explains its managing director Miluše Ryznarová.
The responsible IT company Enlogit from the Ústí nad Labem region, on the other hand, cares about the health of its employees and has therefore purchased ergonomic armchairs and keyboards for all its notebooks, promotes home work among its employees and uses cartering services offered by a sheltered local workshop for company events.
"In addition, we support the Foundation "People in Need", which provides concrete help to the local Roma community," says Ondřej Suchý, the company's representative.
Last but not least, the activity of the cleaning company "Praní a čištění" from the Karlovy Vary region is worth mentioning, which contributes extra bonuses to its employees' pension insurance.
"We provide our employees with contributions for meals, commuting, improving their qualifications and holidays," says Josef Strapáč from the construction company Czasch from Bruntál, the winner in the Moravian-Silesian Region.
All district finalists of the Vodafon Company of the Year competition were automatically registered for the category Responsible Company of the Year, who answered the questions of the questionnaire enclosed with the registration and sent it to the organizer by August 15 at the latest.
Incorrect or incomplete answers in the questionnaire were excluded from the evaluation by the organizer.
"If the representatives of the competing companies left the questions unanswered, they were excluded from the "Responsible Company of the Year" competition, but they were not disqualified in the main competition Vodafone Company of the Year."
"A separate registration only for this competition is not possible, as it is only a subcategory of the main competition Company of the Year," explains Karel Goldman of the organizing agency Bison & Rose.
Pilsner Bodenfonds - Police arrests in a public tender
In the building of the Land Fund in Pilsen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The local media entrepreneur and real estate dealer Luboš G. was taken away by the detectives in handcuffs.
The latter had allegedly attempted to manipulate a public competition currently taking place for the settlement of restitution claims in such a way that the land offered in the competition fell to a specific interested party.
He is said to have paid Luboš G. half a million for it.
"At this stage, I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for the crime of fraud in a public competition," Antonie Zelená, head of the Pilsen prosecutor's office, told the newspaper "Právo", adding that she could not provide further details in view of the ongoing investigation.
24 hours later, the 46-year-old entrepreneur was released by the police.
How he was able to manipulate public competition can only be speculated about in view of the scarce official information.
In response to Právo's question, Lubomír Černá's spokesperson for the Land Fund stated that the police had indeed made arrests in the Pilsen branch of the Land Fund during a public competition.
"It was about a client and by no means about one of our employees," she concretized.
According to Ms Černá, the public competition had the correct name 'invitation to tender for claims for the transfer of land under the Land Law' and would take place in cases where several applicants showed interest in the land offered.
"These persons offer, in the context of the request, a higher value of their restitution claims to be settled by the transfer than the value of the land proclaimed."
"According to the claims offered, the order of potential buyers is determined, then the land fund transfers the property to the person with the highest offer," explains the spokeswoman of the fund.
Luboš G. obviously had information at his disposal as to who had registered in response to the request and, since he himself was a entitled person, since he had bought a number of restitution claims, he offered a property interest to withdraw from the competition.
Obviously against a fat severance payment.
That would also be a sufficient explanation for why he had such a large amount of money with him when he was arrested.
Luboš G. already had very good contacts with the Pilsen Land Fund in the past.
He also played a role in the case of the former head of the land fund Václav Sankota, who was prosecuted because he gave up land in substitute restitutions for which location decisions had already been made for construction projects.
At that time, Luboš G. also acquired land from the Land Fund, for example, intended for the construction of public roads, more precisely, on the site where the construction of the access road to the Borské pole industrial park was planned.
Later, he exchanged them very cheaply with the magistrate for a house directly in the historic center of the city, which far exceeded the value of the land.
At that time, the town hall had to give in with a heavy heart in order not to endanger the construction project by blocking the plots.
Household housing costs rise by several hundred per month
From January, households will not only have to reckon with higher costs for all types of energy, but also with higher water and sewage charges and for district heating, and in some places rents are also rising.
From January, families will have to pull several hundred crowns more out of their wallets each month than before.
Electricity will be up to 4.6 percent more expensive, gas by 2 percent and more, in some cities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supplies and in some places district heating supplies will also become more expensive.
The increase in electricity alone costs households several hundred crowns more every year.
Heavy electricity prices were reduced by all main suppliers, so the significant promotion of electricity generation from renewable sources, especially from photovoltaic systems, is to blame.
Gas is only moderately more expensive, but exactly when people need to heat the most and have the highest consumption.
Here, too, a few hundred crowns more per year can be expected.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive throughout the Czech Republic, the prices for district heating vary from city to city.
Larger towns in particular are planning price increases.
For example, households in Pardubice and Hradec Králové will have to pay up to 50 crowns more per month for district heating from January, and families in Liberec will have to pay more than 1,000 crowns more per year.
The inhabitants of Prague, in turn, are threatened with 9 percent higher water and sewage charges in the event that the city increases the infrastructure rent.
If the rent does not change, it is only 6.8 percent.
However, the price in Prague is still among the lowest compared to the whole of the Czech Republic.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sewage charges are expected to rise by 7.4 percent.
Enormous rent increases are to be expected, for example, in 140,000 rental apartments, where the so-called rent regulation will cease to apply from January.
For example, the housing company CPI Byty, which owns 2500 apartments in Ústí nad Labem, plans to increase rents by one hundred percent from January.
Anyone who does not agree with this rent increase will be prosecuted by the company.
Regulated rents, which are still paid today in almost 300,000 apartments, are expected to rise by more than 10 percent next year.
Czech kids get drunk with Fernet and rum beer is out - it just seems too slow
Fernet, rum and vodka, for once also a good whiskey, which was stolen from the father's house bar.
These are the drinks after which drunken Czech teenagers under fifteen most often need emergency treatment.
No exception are children who have to sleep their hangover repeatedly in the hospital.
This is evident from the experience of doctors who are faced with similar cases in the reception of the children's wards of clinics.
"Beer or wine are completely out of fashion because it just takes too long to get drunk."
"Today's trend is clearly hard alcohol," said Právo Luděk Pelikán, the chief physician of the children's department at the Hořovice Central Bohemian Clinic.
"Whisky, if you manage to steal a bottle from your father's bar, and if not, then at least Fernet or vodka.
"Vodka has the advantage that you can mix it with juice, then it does not smell so strong," explains the chief physician.
The spokeswoman of the Faculty Hospital Motol Eva Jurinová agrees with him.
"Most often it's about Fernet or Rum."
"This is today's alcohol trend, especially in primary schools."
"Occasionally, it was also about Slibowitz, who you take from home," said Mrs. Jurinová.
According to chief physician Pelikán, thirteen or fourteen-year-old drinkers are no exception in hospital admission.
In front of the clinic in Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for ten years in the pediatrics department of the Motol hospital, where ambulances delivered drunken students from near and far.
"One girl had to be hospitalized four times."
"She began her career at the age of 12, when she was admitted for the first time with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood and in combination with 'ecstasy'," the doctor described a particularly serious case.
"She was at some dance party in the exhibition grounds in Holešovice."
"The interesting thing was that it didn't seem strange to her mother that her daughter didn't come home for 48 hours," says the chief physician.
Especially the lack of interest of the parents or their incredible tolerance when toasting with their own offspring is considered one of the main causes of the growing alcoholism of children.
According to experts, real dependence in the true sense of the word is not about children.
"Alcoholism is a long-term chronic dependence on alcohol and all the associated phenomena and this is not the case with these children."
Those who repeatedly consume alcohol usually have a negative family-social background," explains chief physician Pelikán.
According to the spokeswoman of the Motol hospital, Mrs. Jurinová, about forty drunken children had been admitted to the local Department of Pediatrics and Adolescent Medicine by mid-November.
However, only cases of severe alcohol poisoning that required hospitalization are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are brought home after outpatient treatment by their parents or, if applicable, by the police will not be registered.
In addition to the cases in which children only drink such a bottle of liquor at school, Mr. Pelikán believes that there are three seasonal amplitudes that can be relied on one hundred percent: Walpurgis Night, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"The latter for two reasons - either out of grief because of the bad report card or out of joy for the holidays."
"On Walpurgis Night, I have already experienced seven drunken children at once in the recording," emphasizes Doctor Pelikán.
A drunken child who spends the night under medical supervision is paradoxically better off than a child who only has to deal with an unpleasant hangover the next day.
The headaches of the morning after, which result from dehydration and lack of glucose, can be dispelled in the hospital with a fluidizing infusion with glucose and nutrients that the organism lacks.
"They are clearly better off, because after the "wonderful" experience in the evening, they wake up in a good mood without anything hurting anywhere."
"They're just a little confused about where they are," admits Doctor Pelikán, sometimes at least spoiling the patient's good mood by telling them the cost of treatment.
Because the transport by ambulance and the night in an acute bed come well and gladly to a few tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time I used this as a means of education, when I calculated directly to the children during the rounds what their drunkenness cost and that it may well happen that they have to work all the holidays to earn the money for a single such party," added Doctor Pelikán.
In his opinion, however, the health insurance companies do not resort to recourse procedures to claim the costs necessary to cure the drunken children from the parents.
Two L-159 training aircraft in foreign hands for the first time - in Spain
Two L-159 light fighter jets out of a total of five, which the Czech Ministry of Defense has exchanged for the Casa C-295M transport aircraft, flew on Tuesday to the Spanish city of Seville, where the Spanish aircraft manufacturer Casa - EADS is based.
It is the first time that machines of this type are in the possession of a foreign army.
Abroad, they have so far only been seen at maneuvers or air shows.
This is the airworthy two-seater version L-159T1, which was operated by the Czech army.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat L-159s.
These are currently still preserved in Aero Vodochody, the broker of this business - the company Omnipol - took them over last week.
Jan Pejšek, the spokesman for the Ministry of Defense, does not yet know when it will physically dispatch the planes from Vodochody.
The single-seat L-159 fighter aircraft, in turn, were separated from long-term stored aircraft without further deposits and investments on the part of the ministry.
"The two-seat L-159T1s were replaced in their current condition and appearance," Pejšek told Právo newspaper.
He added that the army would not have to do without two-seat fighter jets, as the Ministry of Defense signed a 200 million contract with Aero Vodochody in May 2009 for the conversion of four superfluous L-159s to the two-seat version.
A new aircraft took over the army in July, the second it wants to take over by the end of this year.
According to Pejšek, EADS has committed itself to enforcing the fighter jets into the equipment of one of the NATO countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is a customer for L-159 aircraft and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO countries.
"It is therefore up to the customer how to implement the item," Pejšek said.
The business newspaper (HN) had previously reported that the Spanish government has no interest in the L-159.
The barter of five L-159s for a Casa transport aircraft and the purchase of further aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns had been approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
At that time, the Ministry of Defence had not put out to tender for the purchase, but approached EADS directly.
The defense department at the time argued that this exchange would support the future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought Aero 72 aircraft, of which it uses only 24, the rest they wanted to sell.
By the way, the purchase of the aircraft Casa should also have a judicial aftermath.
The European Commission referred the Czech Ministry of Defence to the European Court of Justice. The reason? It would have had to select the aircraft on the basis of a pan-European invitation to tender and certainly not by approaching a single manufacturer.
The army has already taken over three Casa aircraft, the last of which is scheduled to land at Kbely Airport within fourteen days.
A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
That's the surprising finding of a study published Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty," explained study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health problems, Ms. Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
These men were equally likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
In men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, however, this risk fell by 33 percent, in men up to sixty even by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which form already in prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research found that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
