Fishermen from the nearby town of Bodo now have to row for six hours to get into fishy waters: Ogoniland, located in the heart of the Niger Delta, is considered one of the worst polluted regions in the world.
On the journey through the mangrove swamps crisscrossed by rivers, the full extent of the devastation becomes obvious.
Instead of bright water, the motorboat stirs up brown broth, who dips his hand into the water, pulls out oily fingers.
The roots of the mangrove trees protrude from the ground like black liquorice poles, sadly found palm trees let their fronds hang.
Flocks of birds, as they are otherwise common in wetlands, are searched in vain: As soon as the outboard engine is silent, an eerie calm spreads in the former paradise that smells like a gas station.
"What is happening here is ecological warfare," says Celestine Akpobari darkly: "We live in constant danger to health."
The war comparison is appropriate.
The settlement area of the Ogoni has been a battlefield that has been contested for decades: Here the first explorers from Europe invaded more than 60 years ago, here the first resistance organized in the 80s with the later executed writer Ken Saro-Wiwa, here the Shell Group had to stop its production in 1993 because it became too dangerous for its oil workers.
Even today, the company is denied the return to Ogoniland: While more than two million barrels of black gold are pumped daily from the entire delta region of three times the size of Switzerland with over 5,000 drilling wells and 7,000 kilometers of pipelines, the oil fields in Ogoniland lie fallow, the situation is too unstable for the group.
Every few hundred meters, steel frames rise out of the water like bizarre sculptures: "Christmas trees" are called the heads of the boreholes far too tenderly.
They are up to 50 years old, most corroded to the core.
Again and again such a drill head breaks apart, says Akpobari, then a constant stream of crude oil runs into the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion liters have flowed into the delta's ecosystem in 50 years: year after year, the amount of oil that penetrated into the sea off Alaska during the accident of the supertanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago - one of the largest environmental disasters in the history of mankind.
Who is responsible for the ongoing eco-GAU is disputed.
While the Shell group blames sabotage and organized oil theft for more than 90 percent of the pollution, environmentalists see bursting drill heads and leaking pipelines as the main culprits.
In 2008, US scientist Richard Steiner accused the company of setting significantly lower safety standards in Nigeria than usual elsewhere in the world: the rate of defects in the lines alone was "many times higher than elsewhere".
In a place that looks from a distance like an abandoned, oil-smeared open-air workshop, figures emerge from the mangroves: they are splinter naked and smeared with oil up to their necks.
A fire flickers under one of the many barrels, some of which are connected to pipes, some scattered arbitrarily on the site: an illegal small refinery.
In the barrel, the crude oil is heated over the fire for several hours, explains Michael, the head of the group.
First, gasoline penetrates through the pipes into the collecting pot, later kerosene and finally diesel drip out at the end of the line.
Michael and four employees produce up to four barrels of diesel of 300 liters a day: "That brings us 34,000 naira" - around 22 dollars.
The delta inhabitants take advantage of the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil state in sub-Saharan Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
The ridiculously low diesel price of just under 40 euro cents per liter can still be undercut by the illegal stoves: because they get their raw material for free.
It comes from "bunkerers" who tap into the pipeline network across Ogoniland: According to experts, at least 16 million liters of crude oil are lost every day throughout the Niger Delta.
However, only a tiny part of the provisionally stored raw material is illegally refined: the lion's share is filled into tankers by organized criminal networks, including politicians and high-ranking military officers, and sell it off on the world market.
The activist Akpobari considers the debate as to whether the environmental catastrophe is more due to the activities of the population or the lax mode of production to be purely academic.
"If the oil companies were not perceived as intruders and had not destroyed the livelihoods of the fishermen so thoroughly, there would be no sabotage, theft and illegal refineries."
In the meantime, however, the relationship between Ogoni, especially with Shell, has been so destroyed that only a withdrawal of the group would be possible: "Maybe other nationalities such as the Chinese will turn out to be better."
Michael gets nervous.
"It's high time you disappeared," says the muscular oilman.
"The soldiers can come any minute."
If the illegal oil refiners are caught by the special unit of the armed forces, they are not threatened with arrest, but a painful bribe.
Like all Nigerians, the soldiers, who mainly come from the north of the country, also want to benefit from the raw material.
"This damn stuff has brought our country to the dog in every way," says Akpobari.
