The democracy movement in Latin America is getting stronger, as is the support for private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These are the findings of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts stand out in this year's September and October surveys.
Firstly, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has risen sharply (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing at an annual rate of about 6% since 2002, the number of people in favour of democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year's sharp slump.
But only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region's most populous countries, are staunch democrats, lowering the regional average (see chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice. This is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% trust their government. Both figures are the same as last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to achieve democracy.
That this continued during the Great Depression may be due to the fact that Latin American countries experienced only a brief period of recession and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were supported by a stronger social safety net.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, Latin America's poverty rate rose only marginally in 2009 and has fallen 32% again this year.)
However, there are strong differences in sentiment from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread progressive mindset.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more pronounced and violent crime has increased.
For only the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see crime in their country as a bigger problem than unemployment (see chart 5).
About 31% say that either they or a family member have been victims of a crime in the last year. But from 38% last year, the figures have fallen, reaching their lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic output is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market economy: about 71% of respondents nationally stated that the private sector is indispensable for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of a private sector), even though their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, nationalizes many private companies.
Brazil has the largest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with Venezuela taking over this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An electoral setback
No one expected that the November 28 elections in Haiti would be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of the election workers who rushed to the aid of the troubled country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes, ballot papers in the gutter, destroyed polling stations and intimidation were only part of the problems.
Polling stations opened hours late.
Many Haitians, many of whom had been displaced by the January earthquake, roamed in search of choice.
Some eventually gave up altogether.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some presumed frontrunners, demanded the annulment of the election results due to alleged fraud.
Throughout the country, there were partly violent protests.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as "quite good in many respects".
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "These irregularities, serious as they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, allegedly beholden to the unpopular outgoing president René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected run-off election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity suit.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support from voters, is declared the winner of the run-off by the electoral authority, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims still live in tents, a low voter turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for voting had not yet been distributed.
The stakes are high.
Donor countries see a legitimate, recognized government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
Haitians themselves agree.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following her husband's sudden death, Argentina's president, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that pushed her popularity rating up 20 points to over 50%. This is the highest value since her election in 2007.
Whether this will help her win re-election next year, however, depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs of this are ambiguous.
Néstor Kirchner, who continued to direct economic policy after his wife's election, often drew up budgets that did not take full account of tax revenues, economic growth, and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenue as they saw fit.
On paper, the Fernández government lost its majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further discord.
Some dissidents from the ranks of the ruling Peronists lined up behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (in which one lawmaker slapped another in the face and others accused the government of bribery), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to discuss it," the president said.
The 2010 budget now applies to next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend money as she sees fit.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and wage demands by the unions - push the figure to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction to be his main goals, not reducing inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector, and purged the National Institute of Statistics and Census (INDEC), which then glossed over official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
It has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to talk.
And according to official statements, wage increases will be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given a strong boost to the economy.
But inflation undermined the growth spurt through a major devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason, Cristina Fernández wants to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government reached a deal with security holders who had opposed the country's earlier debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for a deal with the backers from the Paris Club, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always refused a review by the IMF, as was customary elsewhere.
But last month, Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund would provide "technical assistance" in compiling a new national consumer price index. It looks like this is the first step in cleaning up INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after her term ends without the support of her husband.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which for the most part has had enough of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy they received will have subsided.
If she wants to win another election, she must decide whether to quietly overturn many of her husband's political decisions.
Weak applause for China
Taiwan's voters are slowly approaching closer ties to the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
On 27th November more than 7.5 million voters, or 70% of all eligible voters, set out to elect mayors and councillors in the five districts. This is seen as a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
By building groundbreaking business relationships, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma herself is a symbolic figure of relations with the mainland. His policies have permanently changed relations with mainland China for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but only barely.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) has three of the five mayors, it did not receive a majority of votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which advocates greater independence for Taiwan, received almost 50% of the vote, while the KMT received 45%.
In a presidential election, this would have meant problems for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party's share of the vote has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP even entered the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election, Taiwanese incidents occurred, such as truck convoys with rioters, flag-waving mass parades and scantily clad dancers.
There was even the obligatory, mysterious assassination attempt.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech on a KMT candidate on the eve of the election,
when a man from the crowd shot him in the face. Lien was wounded and a bystander was killed.
Bizarrely, it is not clear whether the shooter wanted to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Regardless, according to DPP leader Tsai Ing-wen, the attack affected the election and cast the DPP in a bad light, giving the KMT more votes.
Perhaps China was the biggest winner of the campaign.
Remarkably, relations with the mainland were not addressed.
Instead, the candidates debated plans for social housing and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their de facto independence and reject China's military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to put its relations with the government in Beijing in the foreground.
But this time, the DPP also avoided stirring up anti-Chinese sentiment too much.
She was responding to the new awareness that Taiwan's economy cannot survive without China.
Ma, for his part, wants to confirm that the majority of Taiwanese support his China policy.
The government in Beijing will continue to pursue its strategy of attracting Taiwan back to the Community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
Certainly, it also wants political integration. But first things first.
It prefers to wait until after the 2012 presidential elections.
The DPP has since reinvented itself.
Two years ago, it was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was in prison for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he vehemently advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai's rule, a new generation of moderate politicians has developed and the DPP is fighting for the votes of working people and youth.
Tsai found broad support as the DPP's presidential candidate, as did Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything it can to show that it too is capable of establishing close relations with Beijing.
Tsai is planning a think tank as a point of contact between the DPP and China. However, this requires unprejudiced discussions.
Tsai publicly declared that her party offered a "trustworthy alternative" to Ma's premature rapprochement with China.
Chen seems very upset about this change.
From his cell, he declared that the DPP candidates had done better to insist on Taiwan's independence.
He even called on the pragmatist Su to renounce the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen's interference, the DPP is struggling to elect its potential candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Ma's scores are poor, despite rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
According to a KMT spokesman, he will redesign his cabinet as well as local facilities.
The strong presence of the DPP suggests that Taiwan is only partially in favour of rapprochement.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "there is already no turning back."
