Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new forms of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign bacterial species that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two options."
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"That makes it very special, even though it's almost a kind of 'alien' life form," explained Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears Thursday in the online issue of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But as the scientists discovered, the bacterium continues to grow in California's Mono Lake even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"One wonders what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar, co-author of the report at Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study looks at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can set biochemical processes in motion with the help of other elements, and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely vital are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Milton Keynes Open University in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty because it shows that in fundamental biochemical processes and structures, one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Because arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she hypothesized that microbes exposed to both could potentially replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic has a different effect than phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it smears almost everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
According to Jamie S. Foster, associate professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new. But so far, there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than in the early geological era," says Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and National Health Administrations.
Other stolen show dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four show dogs stolen outside a Bellflower motel were found, according to the Los Angeles County Sheriff's statement Thursday.
The four show dogs — two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis — disappeared Tuesday when unknown persons stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van in which the animals were housed outside a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were discovered Wednesday afternoon, and the last two on Wednesday evening, said Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is that the dogs are doing well," Whitmore said.
"They are in good condition."
"They have been returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not specify where the dogs were found, nor the circumstances that led to their discovery.
"The investigation is still ongoing."
"We don't want to say more," Whitmore explains.
"We are following some leads."
