The lion roars again after court approval of MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light for a new beginning.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially approved the "preparing" plan to pay off $5 billion in debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to make new movies and TV shows.
According to Thursday's statements, the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy law, so nothing stands in the way of MGM's relaunch under the leadership of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment. Barber and Birnbaum will head the somewhat slimmed-down studio as managing directors.
The number of employees will be reduced from over 400 to approximately 320.
For MGM, Chapter 11 will not actually go into effect until JPMorgan Chase has closed a planned $500 million bond to fund MGM's new productions.
At the moment, a consortium of the investment bank, which itself brings in $75 million, leads the company. The financing should be in place by mid-December.
The restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 with the assignment to investment bank Moelis & Co to help the company's management, which was struggling with interest payments of $300 million per year, solve their financial problems.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO at Enron and restructuring expert best known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper's efforts to solve MGM's financial worries and pay off the studio's more than 140 Gläuber took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided at the end of 2009 to put the company up for sale.
But the auction attracted few bidders and none wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by creditors.
It all started all over again this spring when the MGM team began the restructuring plan, which was finally signed by creditors at the end of October after months of debate and internal disputes.
If MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multi-million dollar bonus for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, amounts to $9.5 million.
Cooper, who were paid $375,000 per month to run the company, will receive a $4 million "success bonus."
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM. That year, the studio released only one film and created an annual schedule of seven or eight films scheduled to hit theaters in early 2012.
They are also planning two films based on "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio requires a separate bond of between $265 million and $275 million for its financial share of these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who financed about 18% of MGM's loan, attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the final negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any result.
Tech Toys keeps your gift budget in balance
This year's favorite among gifts is the iPad, possibly followed by a Microsoft Kinect video console. Both gimmicks can tear a considerable hole in your gift budget.
An iPad costs as much as five BMX wheels for $99, while the price of a Kinect game is about 10 classic skipping ropes or about 48 cans of Play-Doh.
But you can save your gift budget.
Recently, looking for three electronic toys under $80, I visited three national toy retailers — a Wal-Mart, a Toys "R" Us, and a BJ's Wholesale Club.
I immediately realized that Moore's law had come into effect. This year, the technology toys are more powerful and at the same time cost slightly less than last year.
And although fewer new toys appear with their own website, there is a wider range on the best known of this kind, Webkinz and Club Penguin.
More and more button cell-powered toys are coming onto the market, and many include rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(Unless otherwise stated, all prices are from Toys "R" Us.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, for children ages 3 and up) are plush figures, the size of guinea pigs, that sing a note when pressed on their belly.
Press once corresponds to a note, by pressing several times you can play a song.
Several sing-a-ma-jigs sing in harmony.
Attention: Once you start pressing, you can't stop.
For a combination of sand and dance, the Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price $60, for children from 2) is the best choice.
Based on the Elmo Live technology developed last year, the animatronic doll offers interplay such as 'Simon says', and thanks to the innovative hinged feet with wheel locking, it dominates the moon walk.
