Police operations in China are getting softer
Like a training officer, Tang Shenbin walked across a city square, checking on his nervous subordinates and giving orders with military authority and a hushed voice.
He wanted his female members of the Chengguan—China's rugged guardians of urban order, feared and despised for their arbitrary raids and propensity for violence—to impress viewers.
"Stand straight!"
"Look straight ahead!"
"Show them," he whispered to them, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls, barely out of their teenage years, with white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and trousers stood tight.
Four pairs of black pumps stood in a straight row.
Four neat hats sat perfectly on the hair held with blue and white striped bows.
"They look average to me," Mr. Tang remarks disdainfully.
"Models are pretty."
Several governments have already tried to burnish the image of China's city inspectors.
In a city, all new applicants must have a college degree.
Guangdong province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the gray-green one.
Wuhan in central China replaced violence with staring down: In 2009, 50 officers reportedly circled an improperly set up food truck and stared at the operator until he packed up after half an hour and left the square.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, wants to fundamentally change its image.
Since 2003, 13 women have reinforced the city's police patrols. They were specially chosen for their appearance, good figure and youth.
They are intended to give the rough-hewn police a softer, feminine aspect.
Unfortunately, Scarlett Johansson would hardly succeed in improving the bad image that the Chinese have of these city commandos.
And rightly so, according to the critics.
Unlike the police, these officers can only enforce city laws through fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely paints a different picture.
In January 2008, officials in Hubei province beat an onlooker to death when he filmed them using his cell phone to crush a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual of Beijing officials was stolen and published on the Internet. It describes how criminals can be beaten without bloodshed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon trader suffered brain injuries after a scuffle with five officers.
