Prosecutor will not indict Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have acquitted Senator John Ensign of charges brought against him following his affair with a former election aide and his attempt to get her husband lobbying, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
This decision ends the most serious legal charge against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada. Until the scandal, which made national headlines and put a damper on his career, he was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
As Senator Ensign's office announced, he was "delighted" with the verdict after the year-long investigation.
However, the Senate's ethics committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign's lawyers, they have been informed by the Department of Justice that the investigation against Senator Ensign has been dropped and that there are no further charges in this matter.
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The verdict came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department. In their opinion, there was sufficient evidence that Ensign violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails, and other documents first disclosed in the New York Times in October 2009 suggested that Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of his election aides, win lucrative contracts to buy his silence on an affair with Hampton's wife, Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during one of Ensign's election campaigns.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton work. According to the documents and interrogations, he took over lobbying for her after Hampton was hired.
Since Hampton was recently on Ensign's election team, he was not allowed to lobby for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called turn-door lobby ban.
According to the published evidence, "it appears to be collusion and a violation of revolving door statutes," according to Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Justice Department officially declined to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the Department appeared very cautious about taking political charges after a host of defeats that were followed with great interest by the media, including last year's decision to drop charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for wrongdoing by the prosecutor.
Prosecutors "are obviously scared," said Melanie Sloan, president of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington (an organization whose goal is to combat corruption in U.S. parliamentary and government circles), a group of lawyers that has brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to court.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead defense attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day telling him that the department would not bring charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's defense attorneys had cooperated with prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, had "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he had made to prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of the conversation between the Justice Department and me. Suffice it to say: we believe we have made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Electoral Commission decided to drop the investigation into a separate lawsuit by the ethics group alleging that a $96,000 payment from Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal elections law.
The electoral commission said there was not enough evidence that the money was anything other than a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that long supported the senator, was one of the firms where Mr. Hampton found lobbying work thanks to Mr. Ensign's help.
A December 2008 e-mail shows that after the firm advanced Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton in which he told him that he was "knocking" on the door of the Home Office about something.
Mr. Ensign also had lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after it hired Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When information about this affair first came out last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and gave up his position in the Senate, where he had ranked fourth in the Republican ranking.
After many months of unnoticed, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign would no longer be the target of police investigations, his press secretary, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department's lead and drop its investigation.
"Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work in serving the people of Nevada," she said.
