Can politeness connect what divides?
After a campaign of swear words and negativity, little politeness has erupted in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine two-party cooperation or a moment of illusion before quickly returning to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring a breakthrough on the big issues that had to be dealt with during the lame duck session, the session at the end of a term of administration in which no decisions are made.
From what one hears, governing was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor an acknowledgment of their shared responsibility, but rather an empty episode of partisan scoring.
Wednesday's public meeting of the President's deficit commission was also civilized, despite the policy differences that persist among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a test phase - in which one demands from the other sign of cooperation and willingness to compromise, while they themselves try to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of the voters after another party warfare.
Therefore, Tuesday's meeting itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November election gave Washington a mild vote, at least for a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die away again.
And that's a good thing."
On some issues, especially those on the lame duck session agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution."
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one is advocating it.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or even all, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while denying assistance to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, optimism has risen that agreement on these issues can be reached during the "lame duck session" and at the same time ratify the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institute warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the "lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to permanent cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also skeptical – and this skepticism is shared by many – that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening from today until 2012 as a preliminary, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who served their education.
However concerned Republican leaders may be that they are playing poker too high, they know they must try to deliver on their promises to cut government spending and repeal health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, in their own estimation, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan the official recommendation, and they are struggling hard to even come close to that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the body's elected representatives, as there is little room for manoeuvre or sympathy for compromise on financial issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take the form of partisan clashes next year, when Republicans challenge Obama over the federal budget, taxes, and health care, followed later by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It has been proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, both parties must pay careful attention to public reaction.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Bipartisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and they appear to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and congressional Republicans than they were between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
In this sense, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide the two.
