Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School commemorates the man who built it, the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" because of his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the surrender of the Khmer Rouge to the government, long-time supporters in Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that tells the story of the Khmer Rouge for the first time to children of former soldiers.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodia tribunal sentenced a former Khmer Rouge member for the first time when it sentenced former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Alnlong Veng's Khmer Rouge veterans, hampering their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, head of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization that studies the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It divides even families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-Ied government in 1979, remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary fought the guerrilla war from their base in the west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok raised the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to government, leading to the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not relented, was arrested by government forces near the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh prison, awaiting trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled into the gruelling poverty of rural Cambodia, and many remembered the movement nostalgically.
Even though a few elite Khmer Rouge officials kept their local government posts because they laid down their arms, the ordinary soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined Rhmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling down in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Early next year, the court will try to put Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, and Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, on trial.
The court's mandate is to condemn the old leaders and those primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue other acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to alleviate fears in Anlong Veng.
Current media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials of the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
One hot evening, Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the withered grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past at the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
"If there were no more persecutions, there would be war here."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court charged more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
"Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer times means collecting the broken pieces," he said.
"It's our duty to put these broken pieces together so we can understand everything."
The center created the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia."
It distributed the book in Anlong Veng in June as an appendix to the Ministry of Education's high school history book, which contains less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As is often the case in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court," he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people will be convicted by the court."
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process complex and complicated, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are gradually gaining influence," he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a path overgrown with shrubs and filthy with plastic waste leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body had been burned here after his death in 1998 on a pile of tires.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone saleswoman on the side of the road, said she didn't know much about the man who was burned here.
"But he has a strong spirit and many people here go to him to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later in the day she wanted to go to Pol Pot's final resting place, where she will lay a bush of ripe bananas - hoping that it will bring her luck.
