Without wanting to diminish the skills of German driver and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the performance of Renault's engine, the "secret weapon" that the Multi Siemens put into Red Bull's hands and thus created a winning team has become legendary.
In reality, it is a powerful software for simulating processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes not related to car racing.
This computer program, known as PLM, has been used to develop assembly chains in factories around the world, power plants and high-precision instruments.
The aim is to faithfully reproduce or simulate a product or process before it is actually built, in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi's aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial department at Siemens, explains that by using this software in the Formula 1 factory, Red Bull can design and execute the changes and improvements noted during the races and tests "in a few hours, almost in real time".
