Today, Red Bull's team employs 180 highly qualified young people. With powerful computer systems, they carry out analyses and all possible changes to the racing cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all components of Red Bull's race cars, with the exception of the engine, for which Renault is solely responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are changed.
Thanks to advanced production equipment and high-tech autoclaves, the changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours.
The only limit to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million a Formula 1 team is allowed to spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has built its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its race cars in a town 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings in which visits - especially by journalists - are very limited.
Everything that happens there is top secret.
The workforce consists of 580 people, including the two drivers, world champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts at the service of its participation on the racetracks, there are other protagonists whose support is invaluable and whose notoriety is zero.
Steve Nevey, the plant's head of technology, points out that five years ago it could be said that advances in R&D for race cars contributed 50 percent to the victory and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today, the share values have changed. Technology accounts for 85 percent of success, while pilots' contribution is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computing, because they "are unpredictable gladiators".
