Zapatero and Germany's red line
Berlin has decided to keep the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the entire European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment agencies or the abolition of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former government president Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for provoking the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It should be anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake of her public relations work.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which collides with the preservation of the traditional traditions of the majority of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, people in Germany are beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the South would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a transformation of the euro according to German proposals. This means more macroeconomic control; strict financial management; punishing countries that violate the targets; possibly, the cessation of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from 2016.
This was the first sign of the drifting apart between what Germany felt was necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second signal was sent by the Central European country when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At the time, this was strongly criticized. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, public opinion and published opinion were absolutely against bailing out Greece.
After all, Merkel comes out again in the last days of October with a clear position. It calls for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be rescued while obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it advanced the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, was accepted. In the coming months, we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which should make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from that date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area, in which the offending countries will be severely punished, forced to default and, in this case, the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must pursue a hard growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just a question of reducing the national deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will become more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood it that way, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday's meeting with big business and yesterday's announcement of new measures) indicates that despite criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of putting her own house in order has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything will change.
Among the possibilities considered, it cannot be ruled out that we would have to leave the euro area, which is crammed with less serious countries.
In that case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sport and rule evasion
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) from the match on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed about whether it was an unsportsmanlike act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will comply with the prescribed sanction in the next league match against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen over the case stems from the fact that a Real Madrid football club team (which pretends nobility and honour in its anthem and on other occasions punished its players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and the dramatisation by Mourinho, who has added one more episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its purpose.
In this matter, the damage caused to sportsmanship should be investigated.
The sportsmanship defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of clean play is to prevent the offending players from taking undue advantage from the opposing team. That didn't happen either.
The paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand by cheating or circumvention of the rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the intentional fouls.
Here it should be emphasized that the rival was neither put in a less favorable position nor were advantages for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that one's own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team could also be eliminated at some point. In addition, with this approach, players receive a sanction and go to the second card cycle, in which they are eliminated due to accumulation of cards with one card less than in the first cycle.
So it is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices do not go against sportsmanship, which includes strategic decisions to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, players didn't want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule evasion), they rather wanted to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or fleeing from it.
Although the line between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the controversy arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
Offer offensive to catch customers for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
This year, the dictatorship of the calendar drops an avalanche of reservations on the days of 16 and 17 December.
The celebrations paid for by employees themselves are spreading. You don't want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the Turrón and the Christmas lottery, there are also group dinners in the run-up to Christmas, which supply oxygen to Barcelona's catering and leisure industry. But as a result of the economic crisis, they are triggering a price offensive to capture the customer segment, which represents the masses: Almost everyone wants to spend between 20 and 30 euros for a lunch or dinner, confirm the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations.
To make accounting even more complicated, the calendar (New Year's Eve falls on a Friday) dropped all orders in the week of December 13th, resulting in an avalanche of dinner reservations on two peak days (the 16th and 17th) and almost no orders the week before.
