Obama appoints a senior in charge of the fight against terrorism to prevent new revelations.
Interpol issues a red warning to pursue and locate Assange.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth in which the facts are difficult to clarify.
Yesterday, Interpol issued a "red warning" to "find and prosecute" Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest order.
Moreover, it is not new, it dates from 20 November.
It also has nothing to do with the recent revelation of over four million diplomatic documents from the US, but with the allegations of sexual abuse that the Australian has to face in Sweden.
Furthermore, the lawyer of the founder of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange."
Already on the 20th, the international police authority based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but it was not announced until yesterday after receiving the authority from the Swedish authorities.
That is the way things are. The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange "in order to provisionally arrest and extradite him."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, according to the organization, many member countries consider the red warning to be a carte blanche for arrest – which must be carried out by the national police – especially if they have a bilateral extradition treaty, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be staying.
The move outraged Assange's lawyers, who gestures published a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange applied to leave Sweden and received permission from the prosecutor, who is compared to the fabled Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's security chief.
"This is like a hunt, not like a legal prosecution," the letter charges.
While the world searches for him - and his mother protests her son's innocence from Australia - Assange is in an unknown location, but not in silence.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the head of Time magazine via Skype from an unspecified location. During the conversation, he requested the resignation of the Secretary of State of the United States, Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be proven that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN and thus violated international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign," he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the request for resignation "ridiculous and absurd."
"I'm not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website," he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior counterterrorism official, Rusell Travers, with preventing new revelations of documents.
The attempt by President Barack Obama's spokesman to pay less attention to Assange contrasts with the opinions proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House of Representatives' National Security Committee starting in January, has called on the state department to investigate the possibility of putting Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to seize their funds and prosecute anyone who supports or contributes to them."
Tom Flanagan, advisor to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone further, and he had to retract his statement that Assange must be "murdered."
"Obama would have to turn him into a target and use an unmanned plane or something."
Those who did not apologize were Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas, and possible presidential candidate.
"Whoever it was who leaked information in the government, he is guilty of treason and anything that is not an execution is too lenient punishment," he told Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in the ERC with a wink to the Carod Allies
The Republican leader allows the party to hold a secret ballot on his continued existence in office.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the General Assembly principle.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe to avoid for the umpteenth time an internal turmoil in the ranks of the ERC, which is directionless after the loss of 11 deputies and half of the vote.
The party leader is aware that his threat of resignation is not enough for those close to former party leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira. But he also knows that the influence of this sector today is as weakened as its mentor himself and will not give him the same headache as other former currents.
