China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
China's representative said at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and would maintain its offer to eliminate 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China is keeping its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said that in the last four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China's climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programs.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new energy law that includes targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, state authorities have worked with those of the central government and municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and reduction of emissions.
He also said that a number of multi-year plans have already been initiated or completed, both those financed by the Chinese government and those that received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Effective Use Programme, which was launched over the past five years and received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private sources.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another to replace traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another to mitigate and adapt, he explained.
Martin Krol, the government's scientific advisor on climate change in the country, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly believed.
He pointed out that the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy effectiveness has increased by twenty percent in the last five years, and another is expected by 2020, he explained.
