The U.S. changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves to the consulate at the visa application service centres before their interview; Costs become waiting times are thus shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, visa application procedures at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants have to present themselves to the visa application service centres (ASC, the initial letters in English) before their interview at the consulate.
ASC staff will record the applicant's biometric data, which will be verified by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, because it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is delivered.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for dealers and investors.
Those who just want to extend their visa do not need to have an interview at the consulate, they just have to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data is collected at the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
