"I started martial arts such as kung fu and kickboxing in Algeria 12 years ago," explained Zemmal, who has been based in the metropolis since 2008 to develop among the professionals.
Personally, I look for combat everywhere, because for those who don't like ground combat as presented by mixed martial arts, competitions are rare in North America."
Recently, the security guard and UPS employee had given bad news to his rivals by winning two gold medals from World Karate and the Kickboxing Association (WKA) at the World Amateur Championships held between October 23 and 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won the categories of full contact kickboxing and Thai boxing," he explained.
"At the moment I'm preparing for the World Cup at San Shou in China."
"Those fighters from each category who had placed in the top four at the last World Championship had been invited."
"I won bronze in Toronto in 2009."
"I finished eighth in Vietnam in 2005."
"In 2007 I finished the tournament in China in fifth place, while in 2009 I finished third in Toronto," he added.
"It's worth noting that I've made progress in every competition."
"With this rhythm I will be first this time or next year!"
"San Shou" or "Sanda" are disciplines originating from China, in which punches and kicks as well as floor throwing are permitted.
The duels usually take place on a platform, less often in a boxing ring.
The most renowned boxing fighter that has emerged from this type of martial art is the American of Vietnamese origin Cung Le, who is well known in the world of martial arts.
If Nacer Zemmal withheld only one event in his career, he would certainly call his presence at the super tournament "King of Sanda", the Super Bowl of kung fu.
"This competition is the highest-ranking and most prestigious in China," explained the likeable pound guy.
"It's a bit like the equivalent of Lumpinee Stadium (the biggest stadium in Thailand)."
"That was a super experience."
Zemmal had won his first fight in the semifinals of his category (80kg) before losing in the final.
"The one who beat me was a real professional," he said.
"There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 95 kg)."
"The winners of the semi-finals will meet in the final of their category."
"Then the winners of each category stand up to each other to crown a single champion, the king of kung fu."
450 million in contracts without tender
Hydro-Québec has mutually agreed with project planning firms to award $450 million in contracts for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydropower project.
In the middle of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts stands a consortium consisting of the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has received the most important share, namely that of the project management, for a sum of 295 million dollars without a tender.
This consortium, called "Énergie gérance", was formed in 2004 as a byproduct of Hydro-Québec's decision to hand over to the private sector its responsibility to hand over this important hydroelectric project to the tune of 5 billion dollars.
At the beginning of 2005, the consortium "Énergie gérance" won the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Parti Québécois, recourse to consortia of companies is a serious ethical problem which creates the risk of exclusion of competition and an increase in prices.
"This is a new way of rigged play and weakens the competition."
"This means that instead of rigged games, instead of secret games, you are now conducting them in an open form," PQ MP Sylvain Simard told the press conference yesterday.
In the early morning, Simard had raised the question before the National Assembly, because it seems difficult to him to understand how the interest of the public can be served in this way.
Resource Minister Nathalie Normandeau had responded in the afternoon by vehemently denying that this contract had been a rigged game.
"I remain true to my line," she railed, reiterating that the PQ had acted "dishonestly" and that it "lacked toughness."
She said it was "the minimum" for the PQ to apologize.
The consortium's model is common practice worldwide.
It is usually a temporary alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their expertise on a bid on a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity in terms of the scale of its work.
The construction process is underway and should be completed by 2012.
Nevertheless, the contract was awarded without any competition being able to take place; there had already been negotiations.
Moreover, the consortium's model in Quebec is no longer an exception, even for relatively simple projects.
As the newspaper "Le Devoir" noted last week, the consortium's model applied in the field of civil engineering and consulting is the subject of government investigations.
A quick scan of the Quebec Business Register reveals more than 200 consortia, some of which appear to be of permanent duration.
In this way, Dessau, for example, works in partnership with the majority of its core competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin or Roche and Tecsult.
Any link, and there are several dozen of them, goes back to one and the same legal person, namely Dessau.
As far as the "Énergie gérance" consortium is concerned, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the territory of Baie James is subject to a special labour dynamic and that Hydro-Québec has been paying particular attention to this fact since the 70s".
Réal Laporte, the major employer of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has issued a statement that turned up its nose at the fact that the project management contract was approved by agreement.
"If you advertise and there are few applicants, your prices will skyrocket."
"So you have two options: either you take the people who are on this market and tell yourself: they will negotiate a satisfactory agreement at a good price."
"The idea, however, is that it is not the price that is decisive, but the expertise of the people," Laporte affirmed.
This contract, granted to the "Énergie gérance" consortium, is part of a long list of contracts for more than 50,000 dollars received from the Parti Québécois.
The contracts have been approved by either Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After review, the newspaper "Le Devoir" counted more than 100 engineering and consulting contracts awarded to companies or their subsidiaries, including in particular resource laboratories, between 2002 and March 2010.
SNC-Lavalin had won 22 contracts, Génivar 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not counting their participation in "Énergie gérance".
All these contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the $295,131,564 contract with Énergie gérance.
Sylvain Simard had stated that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) were well known to the "Parti libéral du Québec".
Minister Normandeau had hinted that the PQ was equally linked to the companies that "financed" it, before specifying that they were rather their executives.
Barometer of responsible consumption - The "green" label does not inspire confidence
Greener, but outright skeptical.
Quebec consumers have little confidence in the key players of sustainable growth, but neither do they have confidence in the labelled brands or eco-labels that are supposed to guide their choice.
It is a pity, despite the fact that it is bathed in a high-profile universe teeming with information in favour of more responsible consumption: the barometer of responsible consumption has to deplore a lack of credible information, an inadequacy that is a brake on its commitment, as the first reading held yesterday showed.
Although they pushed the consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two-thirds of Quebec's population admits that they do not believe the environmental commitment of companies as much as they do green corporate advertising, according to the sophisticated measuring instrument devised by the responsible consumer center at the University of Sherbrooke.
Another finding: half of the consumers doubt the trustworthiness of the official certificates attached to the supposedly fair products, but also the credibility of the products and brands that declare themselves environmentally conscious, according to the barometer.
Following the same pattern, the politicians' discourse on this topic is taken seriously by only 14.6% of the Quebec population.
Information on responsible consumption, however, seems important to stimulate this segment of consumption, which is currently enlivened by nearly one-third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, the emptiness and dubious nature of the information dampened the eagerness of 46% of consumers.
After the higher price of the products, this is the second brake identified by the barometer.
Moreover, one-third of Quebecers are suspicious of the stated performance of the green products and services they are trying to provide.
According to another communication, more than half of consumers had already changed their habits in 2010, mainly changing the brand of one or more products to express their convictions.
According to the barometer, 61% of them had also preferred purchases from retailers in their neighbourhood and favoured the purchase of food grown in their region.
Greener and more responsible - the eco-conscious consumption index had reached a 64 of the maximum value of 100 this year - the homo consumus of Quebec loves to present itself as the king of recycling, trying to reduce its footprint in the environment by caring about animal welfare.
But social and environmental awareness still seems to stop at their cars, according to the barometer: just 28% of Quebecers said they used public transport or preferred carpooling in 2010 to demonstrate their ecological interest.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of respondents to this comprehensive behavioural survey, which feeds stereotypes.
Government bond for the acquisition of eXcentris
The Quebec government, which has been asked by Société Angus and Parallèle to participate financially in the acquisition of the eXcentris cinema complex, agrees to cooperate, but only in the form of a competitive bond.
The developer Angus and the company Parallèle, which had hoped for a donation of seven million dollars from the Ministry of Culture to take over the Daniel Langlois cinema complex eXcentris on the Boulevard Saint-Laurent in order to return it to its actual cinematic function, apparently do not receive what they demanded.
The government has agreed to get involved in this matter, but on its own terms.
Instead of the expected donation, the Quebec government is offering a bond of less than initially hoped for, which could bring about a viable solution on favorable terms, at least according to the sources that can be gleaned from the state rumor mill.
A first action plan and a request for 12.8 million had already been rejected by the Quebec last spring, the request has since been revised downwards again in total.
A proposal together with an action plan has already been sent by the President of the "Société de développement des entreprises culturelles" (SODEC), François Macerola, to Minister St-Pierre, who heads the eXcentris file.
Several days ago, he had sent her a final factual report.
However, the cabinet's counter-proposal was sent to SODEC on Wednesday.
Parallèle and Angus now have until 31 December to respond.
In any case, the premise of the state donation really seems to have been pushed aside.
Let us recall that the Quebec community of owners of the cinemas and cinema complexes had rebelled against a direct state investment in support of the takeover of eXcentris by arguing that the Minister of Culture did not have to provide financial aid for real estate projects there that he had not given to other cinemas.
In contrast, several other market participants in the segment sued for substantial economic assistance.
After the self-financed construction of the cinema, cinema boss Daniel Langlois had presented the auteur cinema in the premises of his cinema complex for over ten years with great difficulty, which could justify the exceptional position on the part of the state treasury.
The lack of cinemas showing independent films is more than evident in Montreal, and eXcentris knew how to keep its clientele engaged.
The Société Angus and the company Parallèle, headed by Christian Yaccarini, are heading for a privately financed campaign, from which they hope to raise a sum of $ 700,000 to boost the acquisition.
Since the spring of 2009, only one screen has continued to show films in eXcentris, namely Le Parallèle.
The aim of the future buyers is to reopen the three cinemas on 27 February next year with the screening of the very successful film by Xavier Beauvois "Des hommes et des dieux".
Christian Yaccarini, however, has not dismissed the newspaper "Le Devoir" and ignores what he and his group think of the downwardly revised proposals that have been made to them.
Mystery of complex Canada revealed
The new American diplomatic leaderships disseminated by WikiLeaks reveal the secret of what the United Nations considers to be the inferiority complex of Canadians vis-à-vis the Americans; but with the same blow they reveal the latter's sense of superiority over Canada.
Consequently, American diplomats are amazed that the Canadian voter does not have Canadian-American relations in mind when voting, and they believe that President Obama's visit would have helped the conservative government push through its 2009 budget!
The four new communications between the American embassy in Ottawa and Washington, which were publicly circulated yesterday, offer even more piquant details than the mere substantial content to nibble on.
A link dated 22 September 2008, i.e. during the period when the federal election campaign was in full swing, reports on the point at which the United Nations ceased to participate in the operations discussed by its political leaders.
To the great astonishment of David Wilkins, the American ambassador in Ottawa.
Mr Wilkins offers various explanations for this situation.
"An almost inherent inferiority complex that Canadians may be much more likely to cause Canadian political leaders to talk about internal issues of everyday life than to pass the buck to the United States in this election (as in the 1988 campaign on free trade)," he describes.
The United Nations, he concludes, is thus "the proverbial Goliath of this election: omnipresent, but potentially too threatening to speak of."
The ambassador understands this "deafening silence" all the less because the two countries have intense political and economic relations.
"Logically," he assesses, "it should be the ability of a candidate, a party and, even more so, a party leader to maintain such an essential relationship that the voter has in mind as a key factor in the election."
The other expression of this sense of importance can be found in the January 22, 2009, message sent by Terry Breese, Chargé d'Affaires in Ottawa, to prepare President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
"Your trip will help ensure the government's survival in the vote of confidence on the federal budget in early February, in which Canada will announce its first deficit in more than a decade resulting from a $30 billion to $40 billion stimulus program," Breese said.
Nowhere did he mention that the government had to adjourn the parliamentary session before Christmas in order to prevent parliament from being toppled by the coalition and the continued existence of the opposition parties in this way would affect the quality of the proposed stimulus programme.
Another message, dated January 2008 and written by Ambassador Wilkins, informs Washington of the increasingly negative image of the dramatic series broadcast on CBC by the United States.
The ambassador is disturbed by programs such as Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O, in which one can observe little subtle allusions to Maher Arar, the "no-fly list" or even abductions for the purpose of interrogations conducted by CIA musclemen.
Yet another communication reports in detail how Hillary Clinten asked her French counterpart Bernard Kouchner at their first bilateral meeting whether Europe was prepared to accept certain prisoners from Guantanamo.
Mr Kouchner is said to have answered yes to the question, but on the basis of an individual case-by-case decision.
At the end of the meeting, "he handed the Secretary of State a paper about Omar Khadr, a 15-year-old Muslim of Canadian origin."
"The Secretary of State has agreed to review the file again."
Finally, let's note that tempers are heating up about the WikiLeaks website.
Tom Flanagan, an old adviser who is very close to Stephen Harper, had declared via CBC that those responsible for this massive leak should be "killed".
He had referred here to Mike Huckabee from the United States.
Worldwide plan to renew lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (CFCs) equivalent to almost one-third of the additional reductions needed to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs released to earth due to lighting would be avoided if the incandescent bulbs, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better still, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to the equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, another 5 Gt would have to be deducted from this balance in order to stabilize the climate increase of 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produces the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs this energy requirement is reduced by a factor of two.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched this week by the manufacturer Philips - this company, by the way, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which gives an idea of the savings potential of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide a collection point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit significantly more mercury to generate the electricity wasted by the white-hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would generate as a result of this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars annually in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion to build.
Côte d'Ivoire eagerly awaits announcement of election results
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has called for the "immediate" publication of the results of Côte d'Ivoire's presidential election immediately after its deadline.
"The Secretary-General underlines the need for the Independent Electoral Commission to maintain its work and announce the preliminary results without further delay," a spokesman for the UN chief stressed.
"It asks all parties and institutions of Côte d'Ivoire to demonstrate their responsibility and to refrain from any initiative until the preliminary results are announced."
Despite pressure from certain foreign governments, the electoral commission had missed the deadline, which was set for Wednesday at midnight, three days after the election on Sunday, without publishing the results.
About forty minutes before the deadline, the President of the CEI had confirmed on television that the Commission would "continue with work" to announce the results.
On Wednesday, there were many calls from around the world for the CEI to finally proclaim the name of the winner of the second round of voting under the outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and his opponent Alassane Ouattara.
However, the Gbagbo camp expects the annulment by the Constitutional Council of "fraudulent" votes in the north by the ex-rebel camp of the Forces Nouvelles (FN) during the failed coup in September 2002.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, head of Côte d'Ivoire's presidential campaign, confirmed that the FN's manoeuvres to intimidate voters in the north of the country had deterred the president's supporters from voting.
The entire election could be annulled if Gbagbo's complaints are taken into account by the Constitutional Council.
However, Gbagbo's opponents are now more of the opinion that the country's highest court is not neutral, as it is headed by Paul Yao N'Dré, a politically close associate with Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a man of the north who denies any connection to the ex-rebels, has judged the delay in announcing the election results "unacceptable" and asked Gbagbo to respect them, even if he did not go so far as to claim victory.
His allies insist that Gbagbo is blocking the publication of the results because he knows he has lost; and filing a complaint with the Constitutional Court after preventing the electoral commission from publishing the results is illegal.
The second round of Sunday's presidential election was seen as the culmination of the unification and reconciliation process of a country that had been divided in two for years.
The United Nations had warned on Wednesday the politicians of the Ivory Coast that they could be held responsible in case of possible riots.
Laurent Gbagbo won the first round of voting on 31st October with 38% of the vote against 32% for Alassane Ouattara, who enjoyed the public support of former President Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
Unemployment rate in France remained stable in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Office (ILO), the unemployment rate in France in the metropolis is stable at 9.3% (including the overseas departments at 9.7%), according to the provisional, seasonally adjusted data published on Thursday by the Federal Statistical Office Insee.
The unemployment rate in the metropolis is established at 2.631 million.
The figures for the second quarter amounted to 9.3% of the working-age population in the metropolis and 9.7% including the overseas departments.
Over the year, the unemployment rate rose by 0.1 percentage points.
On closer inspection, 3.4 million workers in the French metropolis were not employed in the third quarter, but wished to find work; This includes whether they were operational every two weeks or not, or whether or not they were looking for work.
The situation of young people on the labour market continued to deteriorate, with an increase in the unemployment rate of 24.2% in the metropolis (+ 0.9 percentage points in three months, +0.5 percentage points over the year) and 25% including the overseas regions.
In the third quarter, 637,000 of the young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed, according to the ILO.
Seniors, for their part, recorded a slight increase in the unemployment rate of 6.4% in the metropolis (+0.2 percentage points over three months and over the year), i.e. 482 000 people over 50, 6.6% including overseas departments.
Only those aged 25-49 had benefited from the stability of unemployment in the third quarter; 8.3% in the metropolis (-0.1 percentage point over three months, +0.1 percentage points over one year) and 8.8% in France as a whole.
After a dispute over its calculation methods, the Federal Statistical Office Insee has not published monthly unemployment figures since 2006.
Eurostat, the statistical office of the European Union, continues in this method, announcing on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% in France for October (including the overseas departments) compared with 9.9% in September.
