Clotilde Reiss affair: the Elysée Palace exaggerates its mediation function for Syria
Within more than six months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, a young French researcher detained in Iran for "espionage," kept the French public on tent, putting diplomacy on alert and accentuating the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All this under the watchful eye of the diplomats of the United States.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and reviewed by the newspaper "Le Monde" reveal some of the background to this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée had explained its strategy to the Americans, who went so far as to give them advice on how to deal with their own crisis of "hostage-taking" in Iran (a small group of wanderers).
