No online games for young Koreans after midnight
The South Korean government will pass a law called "Cinderella" that will ban young people from playing online games after midnight by blocking their access, government officials indicated.
A bill calling on online gaming operators to ban young people under the age of 16 from accessing these games after midnight will be presented to parliament in December, representatives of education and family ministries said.
"Many children play these games all night long and then have difficulty learning at school and also living a normal life during the day."
"We believe that this law is necessary to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said Jo Rin, the ministerial commissioner in charge of the draft law at the French press agency Agence France Presse.
The online games are then accessible again from 6 o'clock in the morning.
The manufacturing companies have one year to prepare for the application of the law, he said.
