Vengeful hackers and industrious spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a twofold significance.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by an intelligence agency (of any other nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits yield nothing more than what you have been reading for months in any journal (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's frighteningly cartooned profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches.
The rule that secret dossiers may consist only of already known news is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism believe in nothing other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example editor at Libération), who only considers what he acknowledges to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi sent to the State Department by the American Embassy in Rome was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why was there such a fuss about the revelations of these dossiers?
On the one hand, these say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representative tasks, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country is a major blow to the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings less the victims, but rather the "executioners" in distress.
But let's address the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, all power could be concentrated like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of its subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if you consider what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control stop being one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can learn the secrets of power.
But how can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets survive?
True, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secrecy, since it exposes the public sphere; but to expose in the style of WikiLeaks that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets is to deprive her of all power.
WikiLeaks did neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but it did Clinton and Obama any wrong.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a formidable power?
It is obvious that in the future the states will no longer put any reserved information online - this would be tantamount to a notice stuck on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is in vain to hope to keep confidential reports secret over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state traveled on an airplane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships intended only for certain ears be maintained in the future?
I know very well that my prediction sounds like science fiction and novelistic at the moment, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, busily moving secretly along uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere else than in mere memory, and moreover the little written information they have received.  in the heel hidden.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate's espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I've had the opportunity to write that nowadays technology is progressing like a cancer, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with a (telephone) wire.
The (analogue) video cassettes had enabled film researchers to explore a film volume by volume by rewinding from back to front and revealing all the secrets of montage, while the (numerical) CDs today allow nothing more than to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
High-speed trains take three hours from Rome to Milan, while it takes three and a half hours by plane, including transfers.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France glosses over its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the fast-start or premature financing promised by developing countries.
And already the crude French whitewashes are exposed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed themselves to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised €7.2 billion over three years, France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed action report by its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and valued for its intrinsic value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, which puts it on the right track to pay respect for its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look into detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" to ensure that an additional deployment was brought in without being to the detriment of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark they consider best.
The European Commission, for example, has chosen the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained, and will be added 150 million over three years as part of the "Fast-Start" financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the ODA level.
In return, France considered that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks for previous year's spending or at global ODA level.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their own calculation mode.
Some, such as France, find €1 borrowed equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects linked to emission control based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that is collected as the equivalent of one donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan should be counted as a commitment to the donor country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking out 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to see for itself.
France is the only country in the EU that uses loans on a large scale.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) fulfill their obligations 100% with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents and understands it as a comparable stake.
Nice hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates with a double fraud in its fast-start financing: partly with an evolution of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros in the process.
The manipulation of the Treasury (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate, if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter on premature financing is only a small question in a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Be that as it may, it is essential to learn the lesson of this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and compensatory justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could take forward the discussions on the issue of long-term financing (another, crucial and currently discussed issue): it cannot escape the question of "offsetting" or the way in which its loans are recorded.
France could change its position to be as progressive on issues as it is on other issues.
So the hope is pinned on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's near-start and its vision of "offsetting" and the use of loans would, by its very nature, raise the international basis of trust needed for further discussions.
